OK, here's a plan for how we'll prototype this app. Take a look below and customize as needed, or if you're ready, select Prototype this App.

App Blueprint

Bab Al-Rizq

Features

  • Daily Dua Notifications Receive timely notifications with relevant Islamic prayers for seeking sustenance.
  • Goal Tracker Set and track daily and weekly goals related to work and productivity.
  • Prayer Time Integration Integrate prayer times with relevant duas.
  • AI-Powered Reflection Tool
    AI
     Use AI to offer personalized reflections based on user input. The tool will also use reasoning to give advice.
  • "Rizq Map" Display a diagram showing various sources of sustenance.
  • "Gratitude Journal" Provide a space for users to record daily blessings.
  • Progress Statistics Generate weekly productivity reports and visualize prayer frequency.

Style Guidelines

  • Color
  • TypographyHeadline font: 'Alegreya', a serif with an elegant, intellectual feel. Body font: 'Inter', a sans-serif font for clear and easy reading.
  • IconographyUse golden icons of open doors with shining light. (#D4AF37)
  • AnimationUse subtle animations for goal achievement notifications and daily dua changes.

Stack

  • AI
    Gemini, Genkit
    Gemini: A powerful AI model capable of understanding and generating various forms of input, including text, code, audio, images, and video. Learn more
    Genkit: An open-source framework from Google that provides a unified API to access AI models and streamlines AI logic, tool use, image generation, and more. Learn more
  • UI
    TypeScript, NextJS, Tailwind CSS
    TypeScript: A popular programming language that adds type safety to JavaScript.
    NextJS: A popular web framework built on React with support for client- and server-side rendering.
    Tailwind CSS: A popular CSS framework that lets you style components inline with your HTML and maintain UI consistency across your app.

Try fixing this error: Runtime Error: Error: React.Children.only expected...

Hello! It looks like you're running into a React.Children.only error. This typically happens when a component that expects a single child element receives multiple children, which can sometimes be tricky to spot.

I've located the issue in src/components/app-sidebar.tsx. The SidebarTrigger component had the asChild prop, which caused it to expect a single direct child to pass its properties to, but it contained a Button which was not what it expected. I'll correct this by removing the asChild prop.

Here are the changes:

Try fixing this error: Console Error: In HTML, <a> cannot be a descendant...

Hello there. I see you're encountering a hydration error because of nested <a> tags. This is a common hiccup when using Next.js's Link component with custom components.

The problem lies in src/components/app-sidebar.tsx. The Link component, combined with the asChild prop on SidebarMenuButton, is causing an extra <a> tag to be rendered inside another one.

I'll fix this by removing the unnecessary <a> tag wrapper inside SidebarMenuButton and also in the sidebar footer. The Link component will then correctly pass its properties to the SidebarMenuButton.

Here are the changes I'll make:
